Henry Eisenstein’s Real Estate Coaching Review! 👇🏼 

This real estate economy is changing rapidly!

And if you’ve been in the industry for any length of time you understand the effect this market will have.

During the pandemic, my business went from +$100K / Month to $0 in March of 2020...
… And by August of 2020, I was back to +$100K / Month. How?

Because of the shifts I learned and if I didn’t learn them, this economy would have destroyed my business!

I don’t share this to scare anyone but prepare yourself for the storm ahead. Many realtors in your office / possibly even your friends, won’t be in this business in the next 12 months.

So, what can you do to avoid this reality?

As you’re probably aware, I have a real estate coaching program designed to help you net 6 & 7-figures.

As a 2X college drop out, I sought out help & mentorship. In fact, I’ve spent nearly $500K on my education since entering the real estate business nearly a decade ago. No Exaggeration.

For me, it’s not about the money but I believe for should put some skin in the game or you won’t follow through on your promises, which is why I am extending my special offer of the 1st 3 months of coaching for just $1K.

STOP THINKING LIKE A TRADITIONAL REALTOR! 👇

In this market, what got you here won't get you there...

Here are a few ideas if your real estate business isn't growing:

1. Is the type of real estate you're selling: growing or dying?
- Are there more or less of these properties selling this year than last year?
- Will there be more or less of these properties selling next year? (Anticipation is Power)

2. Does your "local market" have enough opportunities for you to earn the type of money you desire?
- If not, consider looking an addition 30-60 minutes outside of your local market for higher priced properties.
- One of my coaching students lives in the suburbs of Michigan & want we discovered is if he sell real estate 45 minutes outside his local market, his commission will 2.5-3X. 

3. Are you prospecting in higher priced areas than you did last year? 
- You are paid for what you prospect. We are know this but are you actually doing it?
- I would recommend you sell properties at least 50% higher in price than you did last year. Take the average priced property you sold last year and go up by 50% this year.

4. What is your commission? How can you increase your percentages?
- What I realized is if I just took a little extra time negotiating my deals, my average commission check would go from $10K to $65K. (6.5X more for basically the same work)

5. Do you sell only one type of real estate or do you work with investors and/or commercial real estate? 
- I used to only sell residential real estate. In fact, in 2019, I sold 116 residential properties before the pandemic. That event made me realize my business was not recession proof...It made me think about real estate from a completely different paradigm. I knew if I wanted to NET MORE MONEY I would need to diversify my approach and become a dynamic realtor.

Memorial Day has always been In interesting holiday to me. 

Not only do I think about all the men and woman who have committed their lives for this country. I also think about all the men and woman who are on the frontlines of the average household. The people who work day in and day out for their dreams. Sacrifice everyday to build a better tomorrow. 

I spent many years working this day while many sat on beaches or BBQ’d with friends and family. 

I remember crying and being down to my last few hundred dollars around this time 8 years ago… 

Doesn’t matter where you start. Progress, over time, with the grit and determination to not stop is the recipe for success in anything. 

Looking back on my nearly 9 years into my entrepreneurial journey, my first 3 years anyone would have agreed based on my results and attitude that it would have been ok to quit. To give up. To throw in the towel. So a matter of fact I did. For about 6-7 months I gave up on my dreams. I was beaten up and tired of things not working out. People not believing in me, people screwing me over, people lying to me, people not seeing what I saw possible… 

Then after many months of sulking, again failing at several side hustles, I had one conversation with my coach that changed my life forever. 

He said “Henry, if you had to only focus on one thing, one business, one industry, for a decade what would you do and why? “

It was in that moment I knew real estate would be it… the first 3-5 months back I made nothing… the remaining half of that year I broke the 6 figure mark. Now after 5 years, millions of dollars and several investment properties, and many amazing team members later… it insane to think this is still just the beginning of a multi decade run. This is me not even 9 years in. All I think about is making the Henry in 10, 20, 30, 40 years from now proud. 

Happy Memorial Day everyone, and remember there are many people out there sacrificing and chasing their dreams and some giving up on theirs. Which will you be? 👇🏼

Back in 2015, I dropped out of college for the 2nd time and went all in on real estate.

The 1st 10 months I went broke and built up a massive amount of CC debt. ($30K to be exact)

Fast forward to 2023 Real Estate has allowed me to have:

* Financial, location and time freedom
* Meeting the love of my life
* Supporting loved ones in ways I always desired

The ability to help 100’s of people & change the trajectory of their lives has been the most fulfilling…

Seeing the faces of others quit their jobs, transform themselves, and their businesses/lifestyle… priceless!

Those are just a few things Real Estate has enabled me to have do.

Things I would tell the version of me that was getting started on this journey: 

* Commit for the long-haul. Buckle up!
* Consistency + hard work is a deadly combination.
* Become OBSESSED with the boring “not sexy” work.
* Coaching is the silver bullet but the price tag scares 99% of ppl

Ego is the enemy of success. Ego looks one way and is afraid to lose power and accept help.

Go harder and figure out where the BIG MONEY is (which is why I chose Commercial Real Estate)

Business sucks when you’re struggling yet the most fun when you’re winning and winning with people you care about.
